          "body": "The chapter's opening oracle identifies Pharaoh with the *tan* — the great monster lying in the Nile (29:3). In ancient Near Eastern cosmology, the chaos monster represented primordial resistance to divine order, the force that must be subdued for creation to hold. Ezekiel deploys this imagery with theological precision: Pharaoh is not merely an arrogant ruler; he embodies the creature who sets himself against the Creator. His defining sin is stated twice in identical language (vv. 3 and 9): 'My Nile is mine, and I myself have made it.' The Nile was Egypt's identity — the source of her agricultural abundance, her economic power, and her religious significance (the god Hapy embodied the Nile flood). To claim the Nile as self-generated and self-owned was to claim the position of the Creator. This is precisely the sin Isaiah diagnoses in the king of Babylon ('I will make myself like the Most High,' Isaiah 14:14) and the sin Paul traces to the root of all human idolatry ('exchanging the glory of the incorruptible God,' Romans 1:23). Ezekiel 29 is one of Scripture's most penetrating analyses of how imperial pride works: it does not deny the gods — it absorbs their functions."
